obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line 7
  line `IV. — P ENALTIES AND C RIMINAL P ROCEDURE`
  line `21. Penalty for breach of provisions as to table of tolls, list of tolls and return s of traffic. — Every`
  line `lessee or other person authorised to collect the tolls of a public ferry, who neglects to affix and keep in`
  line `good order and repair the table of tolls mention ed in s ection 16,`
  line `or who willfully removes, alters or defaces such table or allows.`
  line `it to become illegible,`
  line `or who fails to produce on demand the list of the tolls mentioned in s ection 16,`
  line `and every lessee who neglects to furnish any return required under s ection 12,`
  line `shall be punished with fine which may extend to fifty rupees.`
  line `22. Penalty for taking unauthorised toll, and for causing delay. — Every such lessee or other`
  line `person as aforesaid and any person in p osse ssion of a private ferry asking or taking more than the lawful`
  line `toll, or without due cause delaying any person, animal, vehicle or other thing, shall be punished with fine`
  line `which may extend to one hundred rupees.`
  line `23. Penalty for breach of rules made under s ection s 12 and 19. — Every person breaking any rule`
  line `made under s ection 12 or s ection 19 shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to`
  line `six months, or with fine which may extend to two hundred rupees, or with both.`
  line `24. Concelment of lease on default or breach of rules. — When any lessee of the tolls of a public`
  line `ferry makes default in the payment of the rent payable in respect of such tolls or has been convicted of an`
  line `offence under s ection 23, or, having been convicted of a n offence under s ection 21 or s ection 22 is again`
  line `convicted of an offence under either of those s ections,`
  line `the Magistrate of the district may, with the sanction of the Commissioner of the division, cancel the`
  line `lease of the tolls of such ferry, and make other arrangements for its management during the whole or any`
  line `part of the term for which the tolls were let.`
  line `25. Penalties on passengers offending. — Every person crossing by any public ferry, or using the`
  line `approach to, or landing place thereof, who refuses to pa y the proper toll, and every person —`
  line `who, with intent to avoid payment of such toll, fraudulently or forcibly crosses by any such ferry`
  line `without paying the toll, or`
  line `who obstructs any toll - collector or lessee of the tolls of a public ferry, or any of his assistants, in any`
  line `way in the execution of their duty under this Act, or`
  line `who, after being warned by any such toll - collector, lessee or assistant not to do so, goes or takes any`
  line `animals, vehicles or other things into any ferry - boat, or upon any bridge, at s uch a ferry, which is in such`
  line `a state or so loaded as to endanger human life or property, or`
  line `who refuses or neglects to leave, or remove any animals, vehicles or goods from, any such ferry - boat`
  line `or bridge, on being requested by such toll - collector, lessee or assistant to do so,`
  line `shall be punished with fine which may extend to fifty rupees.`
  line `1 [ 26. Pe nalty for maintaining private ferry within prohibited limits. — Whoever establishes,`
  line `maintains or works a ferry in contravention of the provisions of s ection 13 shall be punished with fine`
  line `which may extend to five hundred rupees, and with a further fine, whi ch may extend to one hundred`
  line `rupees for every day during which the ferry is maintained or worked in contravention of those`
  line `provisions. ]`
  line `27. Fines payable to lessee. — Where the tolls of any public ferry have been let under the provisions`
  line `hereinbefore contain ed, the whole or any portion of any fine realised under s ection 25 or s ection 26 may,`
  line `1. Subs. by Act 3 of 1886, s. 2, for section 26.`
obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_8:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-8
  sectionNo (8)
  orderNo 8
  title `Page 8`
  content obj_root_law_sections_8_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes
  sourcePage 8
obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line 8
  line `notwithstanding anything contained in s ection 17, be at the discretion of the convicting Magistrate or`
  line `Bench of Magistrates, paid to the lessee.`
  line `28. Penalty for rash navi gation and stacking of timber. — Whoever navigates, anchors, moors or`
  line `fastens any vessel or raft, or stacks any timber, in a manner so rash or negligent as to damage a public`
  line `ferry, shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to three mon ths, or with fine`
  line `which may extend to five hundred rupees, or with both; and the toll - collector or lessee of the tolls of such`
  line `ferry or any of his assistants, may seize and detain such vessel, raft or timber pending the inquiry and`
  line `assessment hereinafter m entioned.`
  line `29. Power to arrest without warrant. — The police may arrest without warrant any person`
  line `committing an offence against s ection 25 or s ection 28.`
  line `30. Power to try summarily. — Any Magistrate or Bench of Magistrates having summary jurisdiction`
  line `under Chapter XVIII of the 1 Code of Criminal Procedure may try any offence against this Act in manner`
  line `provided by that Chapter.`
  line `31. Magistrate may assess damage done by offender. — Every Magi strate or Bench of Magistrates`
  line `trying any offence under this Act may enquire into and assess the value of the damage (if any) done or`
  line `caused by the offender to the ferry concerned, and shall order the amount of such value to be paid by him`
  line `in addition to a ny fine imposed upon him under this Act; and the amount so ordered to be paid shall be`
  line `leviable as if it were a fine, or when the offence is one under s ection 28, by the sale of the vessel, ra ft or`
  line `timber causing the damage and of any thing found in or upon such vessel or raft.`
  line `The Commissioner of the division may, on the appeal of any person deeming himself aggrieved by an`
  line `order under this s ection, reduce or remit the amount payable under such order.`
  line `V. — M ISCELLANEOUS`
  line `32. Power to take possession of boats, etc., on surrender or cancellation of lease. — When the`
  line `lease of the tolls of any ferry is surrendered under s ection 11 or cancelled under s ection 24, the Magistrate`
  line `of the district may take possession of all boats and their equipment, and all other material and appliances,`
  line `used by the lessee for the purposes of such ferry, and use the same (paying such compensation for the use`
  line `thereof as the State Government may in each case direct) until such Magistrate can convenientl y procure`
  line `proper substitu tes therefor.`
  line `33. Similar power in cases of emergency. — When any boats or their equipment, or any materials or`
  line `appliances suitable for setting up a ferry, are emergently required for facilitating the transport of officers`
  line `or troops of 2 [the Government of India] on duty, or of any other persons on the business of Government,`
  line `or of any animals, vehicles or baggage belonging to such officers, troops or persons, or of any property of`
  line `Government, the Magistrate of the district may take po ssession of and use the same (paying such`
  line `comp ensation for the use thereof as 3 [the Central Government (where the transport is in connection with`
  line `the affairs of the Central Government) and the State Government in other cases] may in each case direct)`
  line `until such transport is completed.`
  line `34. Jurisdiction of Civil Courts barred. — No suit to ascertain the amount of any compensation`
  line `payable, or abatement of rent allowable under this Act shall be cognizable by any Civil Court.`
  line `35. Delegation of powers. — The State Go vernment may, from time to time, delegate, under suc h`
  line `restrictions as it thinks fit any of the powers conferred on it by this Act to any Commissioner of a division`
  line `or Magistrate of a district, or to such other officer as it thinks fit, by name or by virtue of his office.`
  line `36. [ Validation of proceedings since repeal of Regulation VI of 1819 in Punjab ]. — Rep. by the`
  line `Repealing and Amending Act, 1891 (12 of 1891), s. 2 and the First Schedule, Pt. I.`
  line `1. See now the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1 898 ( 5 of 1974), Ch. 2 2.`
  line `2. Subs. by the A.O. 1950, for “Her Majesty”.`
  line `3. Subs by the A.O. 1937 for “the L. G. ”.`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
